But once you get inside the hinged vault, you can no longer doubt the size of the company whose westernmost gate was the station.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German consortium of the Anatolian-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, which became involved in the game of empires late, intended to realize its ambition to control the Middle East with the help of this railway, which was to lead to Damascus, Baghdad and further to what is now Saudi Arabia.
But German imperial ambitions collapsed during the First World War.
Their tracks were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular troops.
Relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
