Today, however, these gates to Anatolia and further to the east serve – at least symbolically – to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party (ACP) has created a completely new foreign policy for the country.
Relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
Now a new policy is in place - Turkey is engaged.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
