"Auto Bee" Prevents Collisions
To advance in the development of accident-protection technologies, Nissan was inspired by nature this time, specifically by bees.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes the example of flying bees, and thus prevents collisions.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Center for Technical Advancement Nissan Motor Co. robota developed in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Advancement Research of the prestigious Japanese University of Tokyo.
According to Kazuhir Doie, general manager of public relations for technology, research and development of the brand, the BR23C is presented as an extension of the four zones of the Nissan security shield.
The task of the robot is to strengthen the ability to prevent crashes in the cars of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
The most important, however, are compound bee eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees, which allows the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
In creating this visual function, the engineers designed what they called a laser range finder (Laser Range Finder).
It records obstacles up to a distance of two meters in the 180-degree range before BR23C, calculates the distance of the object and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor, which immediately converts it to a collision warning.
“The moment an obstacle is detected, the robot mimics the bee’s movements and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the right or even greater angle to prevent a collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is the fact that all the maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to respond quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Lab and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move up and down or diagonally, its movement is limited to only two dimensions and to the direction it is allowed to rotate its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities as with bees.
In addition to accelerating and slowing, Nissan also used the rotation function to prevent collisions.
“The device only needs to process the information every few seconds and to maintain itself according to that data.
It does not require storing information or logical intuition from previous manoeuvres, so it can function without interruption with just two dozen kB of memory.
It may surprise you, but we’re not talking about the giga or the mega.”
This is the first step in the development of new technologies for instantaneous collision prevention, a technology in which Nissan predicts use in series cars in ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be the integration of the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would bring the driver to the destination while avoiding obstacles on the road.
