A week after revealing their preliminary deal, the two banks explained that MUFG intends to buy 9.9 percent of Morgan Stanley’s common shares for a unit price of $25.25, representing a total turnover of $3 billion.
The agreed price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities as at 31 August.
MUFG is investing another $6 billion in convertible securities, which will provide it with a 10% return and whose exchange rate is $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said the entire operation would be based on an average unit price of $29, or 28% below its current rate.
Morgan Stanley's shares, however, lost 6.79% and rose to $23.07 at around 17.00 Greenwich time.
“This strategic merger represents an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to the Banking Holdings Statute,” said John Mack, the group’s CEO.
The new statute was adopted by Morgan Stanley last week, which is meant to allow him to diversify his activities, but at the same time puts him under the supervision of the Federal Reserve Bank.
Its merger with the MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest ax of Wall Street to take a much more cautious approach than before.
The terms introduced on Monday show, among other things, that the deal has been changed over the past few days: last Monday, Morgan only announced that it would sell up to 20 percent of its shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
“A week ago, we thought,” Toshihide Mizuno, MUFG’s executive director, explained in Tokyo, “that our participation would consist solely of ordinary shares.
However, given the current situation of the economy and the market, we wanted to minimize the risks and also to protect ourselves.”
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay Morgan Stanley’s securities 7% less than their book value.
And the operation will result in a reduction in the profit from the stock by about 20%.
The agreement assumes that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferential securities into ordinary shares in a year if the latter are exchanged for a period of time at a price exceeding 50% of the exchange rate, i.e. around $47.
Morgan Stanley assures that the capital that MUFG will bring will allow it to take advantage of investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its cash.
However, the Spokespersons Group refused to provide specific information on the strategic projects of the two new allies.
After investing in MUFG, Morgan Stanley is expected to boast a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said he had “significantly” reduced his balance sheet since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been challenging for the group, as its exchange rate has halved, while insurance costs against non-payment risk associated with debt have risen sharply.
These costs took up the opposite trend on Monday, but remained high, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other “survivor” of major Wall Street investment banks after the collapse of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the purchase of Merrill Lynch, announced that it had selected $15 billion, partly from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett’s group.
