The proposal, protected by the Correo, which was elected in 2006, also extends the powers of the Head of State, who will be able to perform two consecutive four-year terms and be able to dissolve the House.
Correa has already announced that it will take advantage of this power and will apply for a new mandate in February 2009.
Among other things, the Constitution establishes the principle of free health care and education, which the president began to introduce in a country with 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it also counts on a ban on the presence of foreign troops, ending the agreement between Washington and Quito on the use of the Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. anti-drug operations.
