Benelux Governments State Part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux states will help the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first in Europe to get into trouble due to the expanding effect of the US mortgage market crisis, by partial nationalization: the three countries will support the billionaire money and insurance institution as well.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed to do so at the highest level, with the participation of the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
The Fortis Bank is the first in the eurozone to have entered a major crisis in the wake of the international financial markets crisis, which has been spreading for more than a year, and decisions made in this regard could be seen as precedents in some respects.
According to the decision, which was born on Sunday night, all three states will buy out almost half (49 percent) of the bank’s assets.
With complete certainty, the bank will sell part of its capital shares, especially - mainly insurance - activities acquired last year from the Dutch bank ABN Amro.
Fortis stocks began to fall sharply last week, and in the second half of the week there were already serious signs of a crisis in the institution.
Analysts agree, however, that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is too big to let it go.
The company’s securities fell 12 percent on Friday, to a 14-year low.
Since January, the value of shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
In view of the current prices of the shares, the total market capital value of the group is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company’s chief executives, this is unrealistic.
The company’s management is also blamed for the fall of Fortis’ shares of uncertainty in the overseas market related to the adoption of a $700 billion US package.
On Monday, stocks rose slightly.
On Friday, a new CEO, Filip Dierckx, was appointed as the head of the bank.
The Monetary Institute was also looking for private buyers, but no one has signed up with a more serious offer yet.
The Belgian government has previously announced that investors do not have to worry about losing their money.
The bank’s clients have not yet panicked and the branches have not been attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis Bank has a separate branch and has also bought several leasing companies.
The fox in the chicken
Life and health insurance companies in the U.S., based on data from people buying medicines, often refuse the option of concluding an insurance contract with the applicant.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
“There is a data protection program that binds the use of prescription drug data in any case to the consent of the person concerned.
It has to be in the hands of someone independent, otherwise we entrust a chicken to a fox," said Richard Dick, author of a program designed to monitor drug prescriptions.
Insurance companies make insurance and the amounts paid in the case of insurance incidents dependent on the health status of the interested parties, and if the risk is assessed as too great, the insurance will not even close with it.
Previously, they sent those concerned for medical examinations and entered into a contract only when they knew their results.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper procedure: based on the identification number of the customer from pharmacies, it is easy for him to find out what medications he has bought in the last year and a half, from which the program will produce himself, what he is suffering from the disease and what is his health condition.
For example, if you regularly buy a large amount of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it indicates that you have virtually uncontrollably high blood fat levels, which immediately puts you in a higher risk category.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some of which also determine the risk factor, so there is almost no work left for the insurance company except paperwork, even though they pose minor difficulties.
One of the disadvantages is that lecterns can be used for several purposes, some compounds are used, for example, against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
These represent, from the point of view of commercial insurance companies, a significant risk-increasing factor, whereas the first-mentioned difficulties are not.
In order to request and process the data, special companies have been set up, which before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacists, ask the patient for consent.
They are now forced by the authorities, although they have not been punished for their negligence so far.
Some companies have also recently been processing the results of laboratory tests, which combine with data on the drugs used, so that they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, while controlling their use is becoming increasingly complex.
There is a special law on the protection of health data, but its effectiveness applies only to the providers of health services and the insurer.
The bill, which will give the authorities the power to control companies specializing in data provision, is before Congress.
Richard Dick acknowledges that this is not enough: that is why he has developed his programme in such a way that the transfer of data is bound by the explicit consent of the person concerned.
The other thing is that the authorisation in question can hardly be refused, otherwise the insurance companies will not enter into a contract with it.
So the chickens are only slightly referred to the leaf of goodwill.
